The properties of the carbon dot gel produced were found to be dependent upon the reaction conditions applied. The UV–visible absorption spectra of the carbon dots dissolved in water (Fig. 1
                     ) shows broad absorptions in the range of ∼250–400nm, with two prominent peaks possessing absorption maxima at approximately 285 and 335nm, respectively. The absorbance maximum at 285nm corresponds to π-π∗ transition of sp2 carbon, and the absorbance peak at 335nm is assigned to both n-π∗ character of CO transition and π-π∗ charge transfer [27]. The absorption band at 335nm shows a net increase in absorption as a function of reaction time, as well as a blue shift of approximately 10nm. While a minimal effect of reaction temperature is observed at ten minutes, a large effect is observed after 5h. The band at 285nm appears to decrease as a function of time, as the peak disappears for 180°C from ten minutes to 5h. The broad range of absorbance of the carbon dots led to a range of possible excitation wavelengths for photoluminescence, with a maximum photoluminescence being found at an excitation of 360nm (Fig. 2
                     A). The carbon dots possess tunable emission wavelengths and an overall red shift, with the emission shifting from 347nm at an excitation of 280nm to an emission of 445nm at an excitation of 400nm (Fig. 2B). Quantum yields of luminescence were calculated using quinine sulfate as a reference. The carbon dots produced at 180°C for 10min not only portrayed the most ideal gel like properties, but they also possess a quantum yield of 38.7%, the highest of all the prepared samples (Table S1).

The viscous nature of the carbon dot material was further probed through measuring the crossover frequency. The dynamic moduli G′ and G″ are highly frequency dependent. At low frequencies, G″>
                     G′, indicating predominant viscous behavior of the material, which becomes elastic in nature above the crossover frequency, where after, G′>
                     G″. This crossover frequency depends upon the reaction time of the prepared carbon dot materials. Carbon dots prepared at reaction times of 10min possess higher crossover frequencies than those prepared at five hours. The crossover frequency is inversely related to the longest relaxation time (tmax
                     ) and represents the time taken by the carbon dot particles to disentangle. It has been previously shown that the disentanglement time of samples containing polymeric liquids experience an increase of relaxation time as the chain length, and in turn, the molecular weight of the polymer increase [34]. It is likely that a similar trend is occurring in this carbon dot material. As the reaction time is elevated, the extent of ethylenediamine reacting with citric acid will experience an increase, leading to materials with greater mass, and therefore, greater relaxation time (Fig. 6
                     ).
